Happy Mother’s Day!

I want to wish all the mommas out there Happy of Mother's Day.

To the mommas of littles battling sleepless nights, wiping sticky faces, and potty training, I see you. Don't wish this time away. You will miss it.

To the mommas of school age kiddos, I see you. You're doing a great job. You don't have to do it all. Be gentle on yourself and give yourself permission to say "no" when your plate is full.

For the mommas of seniors sorting through all the emotions of seeing your baby celebrate this hard earned milestone, the best is yet to come!

To the mommas who would love nothing more than to hold their babies in their arms again, I pray for comfort. I can only imagine your pain and know there are no perfect words that I could say that may ease it. Just know I'm praying for you today.

To those of you who have lost your mom, I pray that you smile in remembrance of the lessons she taught you and love she gave you. I hope you are able to share those memories with your families so that her legacy can be carried on. I also hope that there are more smiles than tears in those memories.
.
.
.

The kids are out of school and the transition into summer is in full swing. I'm going to be brutally honest with you. Summer stresses me out. The "juggle" of work and family gets ten times harder in the summer. I often feel torn between my two roles and feel like I'm not giving either my full attention or my best. I also know this is a lie but the devil loves distraction and to rob you of joy. It's a battle I continue to fight.

I've learned that I need to give myself an insane amount of grace during the summer. More importantly, I need to slow my pace and rest more than "normal." Rest isn't something I'm great at.  I've heard it over and over again from other women in business that this can be a struggle for them as well. I'm more of the "push as hard as I can until I can't" person. I don't say this with pride. I say it in honesty and transparency and also to tell you that I, too, am a work in progress.

Although I slip up and fall back into the same old routine, more often than I like to admit, there are some things that I have found that work for me. I thought I'd share in case they may help you too.

1.) Schedule your downtime and interactions with friends and family before anything else.
2.) Set work hours and stick to them.
3.) Know your limits and stick to them. Use scripted emails, text messages, and memorize responses for when you are asked to do something outside of your limits.
4.) Give yourself grace when you slip up. You will and you can start again.
5.) Give yourself permission to do nothing and rest.
.
.
.
